00:10:10,770 --> 00:10:14,460
Well, I've always started with
my end destination in mind

259
00:10:14,460 --> 00:10:15,840
and worked backwards.

260
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:17,580
Of course, I didn't know exactly

261
00:10:17,580 --> 00:10:19,290
what I wanted to do in the future.

262
00:10:19,290 --> 00:10:21,690
However, I had a decent idea.

263
00:10:21,690 --> 00:10:24,090
I then made sure to only listen to inputs

264
00:10:24,090 --> 00:10:25,950
that help me reach those targets.

265
00:10:25,950 --> 00:10:28,470
The clearer your goal,
that easier it becomes

266
00:10:28,470 --> 00:10:31,140
to select the right inputs
to help you achieve it.

267
00:10:31,140 --> 00:10:33,630
So, limit the number
of opinions you receive

268
00:10:33,630 --> 00:10:37,050
and prioritize quality over quantity.

269
00:10:37,050 --> 00:10:39,540
Most people have too many
opinions being thrown at them,

270
00:10:39,540 --> 00:10:41,130
but not from experts.

271
00:10:41,130 --> 00:10:45,480
Cut out general opinions and
instead seek expert advice.

272
00:10:45,480 --> 00:10:46,860
This could come from a mentor,

273
00:10:46,860 --> 00:10:48,570
someone successful in your field,

274
00:10:48,570 --> 00:10:52,350
or even educational videos
from experts like myself.

275
00:10:52,350 --> 00:10:55,320
By doing this, you'll get
more valuable, focused,

276
00:10:55,320 --> 00:10:57,870
and specific guidance for your end goal.

277
00:10:57,870 --> 00:11:00,150
Remember, even when you
work your way backwards,

278
00:11:00,150 --> 00:11:02,610
you still don't need to
know everything at once.

279
00:11:02,610 --> 00:11:05,850
Fully listen and implement
what you learn from an input,

280
00:11:05,850 --> 00:11:08,070
and then when you're
facing another challenge,

281
00:11:08,070 --> 00:11:11,070
you can seek out more inputs
that'll help you overcome it.

282
00:11:11,070 --> 00:11:13,770
If you don't do this, then
you'll get mental fatigue,

283
00:11:13,770 --> 00:11:16,050
which can lead to decision paralysis

284
00:11:16,050 --> 00:11:18,570
where you find yourself
unable to take action

285
00:11:18,570 --> 00:11:20,100
or move forward.

286
00:11:20,100 --> 00:11:23,190
Some people might even
mistake this for being lazy,

287
00:11:23,190 --> 00:11:26,280
but in reality, your brain
just gets overwhelmed.

288
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:29,460
The fifth thing to avoid
is being ego driven.

289
00:11:29,460 --> 00:11:31,320
Let me start by saying this,

290
00:11:31,320 --> 00:11:34,080
arrogant people won't
even finish this video.

291
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:35,940
They think they already know everything,

292
00:11:35,940 --> 00:11:37,980
so, why bother sticking around?

293
00:11:37,980 --> 00:11:39,810
But that's exactly the problem.

294
00:11:39,810 --> 00:11:42,270
Arrogance blinds you to the opportunities

295
00:11:42,270 --> 00:11:44,400
that could genuinely change your life.

296
00:11:44,400 --> 00:11:48,090
Ego-driven people are often
too focused on the big picture,

297
00:11:48,090 --> 00:11:50,490
constantly dreaming of the end goal.

298
00:11:50,490 --> 00:11:53,880
This might sound productive,
but it's a dangerous trap.

299
00:11:53,880 --> 00:11:56,010
When you're always looking too far ahead,

300
00:11:56,010 --> 00:11:59,550
you end up overlooking the
small but crucial steps

301
00:11:59,550 --> 00:12:01,020
that lead to true success.

302
00:12:01,020 --> 00:12:02,610
For example, some might be tempted

303
00:12:02,610 --> 00:12:03,900
to scroll through this video

304
00:12:03,900 --> 00:12:05,580
just to see all seven things

305
00:12:05,580 --> 00:12:07,020
rather than sitting down

306
00:12:07,020 --> 00:12:09,990
and actually absorbing
the knowledge in each one,

307
00:12:09,990 --> 00:12:13,350
but by doing so, they miss
out on the valuable insights

308
00:12:13,350 --> 00:12:15,090
that could fast-track their journey.

309
00:12:15,090 --> 00:12:17,130
When you're too egotistical,

310
00:12:17,130 --> 00:12:20,190
you start to believe that you
don't need advice from others,

311
00:12:20,190 --> 00:12:23,040
especially those who
might know more than you.

312
00:12:23,040 --> 00:12:24,717
You might dismiss the wisdom of people

313
00:12:24,717 --> 00:12:27,810
who have already walked the
path that you're trying to take.

314
00:12:27,810 --> 00:12:29,160
But here's the truth.

315
00:12:29,160 --> 00:12:31,920
True wealth isn't just
about being confident.

316
00:12:31,920 --> 00:12:34,590
It's about having the
humility to keep learning,

317
00:12:34,590 --> 00:12:36,780
to understand that you don't know it all,

318
00:12:36,780 --> 00:12:38,760
and that's where the real growth happens.

319
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:39,870
The more you learn,

320
00:12:39,870 --> 00:12:42,330
the more you realize
how much you don't know.

321
00:12:42,330 --> 00:12:44,880
This is called the iceberg principle.

322
00:12:44,880 --> 00:12:47,580
What you know is just
the tip of the iceberg.

323
00:12:47,580 --> 00:12:50,610
The massive chunk of knowledge
is underneath the surface.

324
00:12:50,610 --> 00:12:52,230
That's what truly matters,

325
00:12:52,230 --> 00:12:55,410
and arrogance makes you
forget that it's even there.

326
00:12:55,410 --> 00:12:58,680
In short, arrogance is
a silent wealth killer.

327
00:12:58,680 --> 00:13:01,200
It convinces you that
you're too good to learn,

328
00:13:01,200 --> 00:13:02,520
too smart to listen,

329
00:13:02,520 --> 00:13:04,680
and too important to take the small steps

330
00:13:04,680 --> 00:13:06,120
that lead to greatness.

331
00:13:06,120 --> 00:13:08,880
The sixth thing to avoid
is passing the blame.

332
00:13:08,880 --> 00:13:10,920
One of my favorite Chinese proverbs

333
00:13:10,920 --> 00:13:13,080
is the man who blames others

334
00:13:13,080 --> 00:13:15,360
has a long way on his journey to go.

335
00:13:15,360 --> 00:13:18,480
The man who blames
himself is halfway there.

336
00:13:18,480 --> 00:13:21,840
The man who blames no
one has already arrived.

337
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:23,910
In front of me, I have two objects,

338
00:13:23,910 --> 00:13:26,340
a magnifying glass and a mirror.

339
00:13:26,340 --> 00:13:28,140
In life, you're gonna have to choose

340
00:13:28,140 --> 00:13:31,140
to reach for either of
these on a daily basis.

341
00:13:31,140 --> 00:13:33,690
You might be thinking, "Mark's gone mad."

342
00:13:33,690 --> 00:13:34,980
But let me explain.

343
00:13:34,980 --> 00:13:37,260
If you choose to pick
up the magnifying glass,

344
00:13:37,260 --> 00:13:40,740
it gives you the ability to
hyper-focus on other people.

345
00:13:40,740 --> 00:13:44,700
This is a dangerous path as
it leads to the blame game.

346
00:13:44,700 --> 00:13:46,290
Look, I do kind of get it.

347
00:13:46,290 --> 00:13:47,940
When anything goes wrong in life,

348
00:13:47,940 --> 00:13:51,240
it's natural to wanna pass
the blame onto someone else,

349
00:13:51,240 --> 00:13:52,470
anyone but yourself.

350
00:13:52,470 --> 00:13:53,670
I'm sure there's been times

351
00:13:53,670 --> 00:13:56,400
when you've blamed your
teacher for a test you failed,

352
00:13:56,400 --> 00:13:59,340
even though you spent more
time binge-watching Netflix

353
00:13:59,340 --> 00:14:00,750
than actually studying,

354
00:14:00,750 --> 00:14:02,340
or maybe you passed the blame

355
00:14:02,340 --> 00:14:04,380
onto the traffic for being late,

356
00:14:04,380 --> 00:14:06,990
even though you left the
house 10 minutes later

357
00:14:06,990 --> 00:14:07,823
than you should have.

358
00:14:07,823 --> 00:14:08,910
But here's the thing,

359
00:14:08,910 --> 00:14:12,000
these small instances of
blame don't stay small.

360
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:13,980
Over time, they grow into a habit

361
00:14:13,980 --> 00:14:16,080
that's hard to break free from.

362
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:18,307
I'm sure you've seen
people say stuff like,

363
00:14:18,307 --> 00:14:20,197
"The government hates young people,"

364
00:14:20,197 --> 00:14:22,777
"The system is rigged
against people like me,"

365
00:14:22,777 --> 00:14:24,907
"My boss doesn't like me,"

366
00:14:24,907 --> 00:14:27,300
"I'm not rich enough to start a business,"

367
00:14:27,300 --> 00:14:30,570
and, "Life didn't give me
the right opportunities."

368
00:14:30,570 --> 00:14:32,940
The more you reach for
the magnifying glass,

369
00:14:32,940 --> 00:14:34,920
the bigger your excuses become.

370
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:37,200
However, if you pick the mirror,

371
00:14:37,200 --> 00:14:38,910
then you instead focus on the stuff

372
00:14:38,910 --> 00:14:40,350
you can actually control,

373
00:14:40,350 --> 00:14:42,090
your own thoughts and actions.

374
00:14:42,090 --> 00:14:45,210
So, to embody the wisdom
of the Chinese proverb,

375
00:14:45,210 --> 00:14:47,310
to be the person who has already arrived

376
00:14:47,310 --> 00:14:48,660
at their destination,

377
00:14:48,660 --> 00:14:51,870
you need to pick up the mirror,
not the magnifying glass.

378
00:14:51,870 --> 00:14:54,840
The seventh thing to
avoid is staying static.

379
00:14:54,840 --> 00:14:57,630
This is your comfort zone,

380
00:14:57,630 --> 00:15:00,720
where you retreat seeking
safety and security.

381
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:03,600
Notice how there are
no gaps in this circle.

382
00:15:03,600 --> 00:15:05,790
Almost like a self-imposed prison

383
00:15:05,790 --> 00:15:08,100
with no way out and no way to grow.

384
00:15:08,100 --> 00:15:10,650
If you're currently here,
then you're not alone.

385
00:15:10,650 --> 00:15:12,000
According to some studies,

386
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:14,820
over half of Brits don't
leave their comfort zone,

387
00:15:14,820 --> 00:15:17,040
and 45% of them are worried

388
00:15:17,040 --> 00:15:19,110
that one day they might regret it.

389
00:15:19,110 --> 00:15:22,080
So, what can you do to
break out of this prison?

390
00:15:22,080 --> 00:15:24,150
Well, you need to expand the circle.

391
00:15:24,150 --> 00:15:25,470
This can be really difficult

392
00:15:25,470 --> 00:15:28,290
when our minds are conditioned
to avoid taking risks,

393
00:15:28,290 --> 00:15:30,840
but it's something I
learned at an early age.

394
00:15:30,840 --> 00:15:32,310
Let me show you how I did it.

395
00:15:32,310 --> 00:15:35,220
When I was younger, my
comfort zone was narrow,

396
00:15:35,220 --> 00:15:37,890
school, studying subjects
I wasn't good at,

397
00:15:37,890 --> 00:15:39,300
like maths and English.

398
00:15:39,300 --> 00:15:42,180
The traditional education
system didn't suit me.

399
00:15:42,180 --> 00:15:44,820
I didn't wanna be a
banker, doctor, or lawyer.

400
00:15:44,820 --> 00:15:46,920
I wanted something more hands-on.

401
00:15:46,920 --> 00:15:49,350
So, I stepped out of my comfort zone

402
00:15:49,350 --> 00:15:51,990
and pursued the apprenticeship
I mentioned earlier.

403
00:15:51,990 --> 00:15:54,060
This created a new space for me.

404
00:15:54,060 --> 00:15:55,950
But I wasn't satisfied yet.

405
00:15:55,950 --> 00:15:57,570
I knew I needed more from life,

406
00:15:57,570 --> 00:16:00,060
so I started experimenting
with side hustles,

407
00:16:00,060 --> 00:16:03,690
which pushed me further
into unfamiliar territory.

408
00:16:03,690 --> 00:16:06,780
Suddenly, the world was
full of possibilities.

409
00:16:06,780 --> 00:16:10,620
The next step was clear,
starting my own business.

410
00:16:10,620 --> 00:16:14,490
This was a pivotal moment
requiring a big risk, a bank loan.

411
00:16:14,490 --> 00:16:17,670
It was the best decision that I ever made.

412
00:16:17,670 --> 00:16:19,380
To expand my empire further,

413
00:16:19,380 --> 00:16:22,020
I traveled to China in
search of a manufacturer

414
00:16:22,020 --> 00:16:24,570
for my own brand of
radio-controlled models.

415
00:16:24,570 --> 00:16:27,060
Despite the language
and cultural barriers,

416
00:16:27,060 --> 00:16:29,940
I managed to build valuable connections.

417
00:16:29,940 --> 00:16:33,180
I ran my business for many
years and enjoyed success,

418
00:16:33,180 --> 00:16:35,370
but eventually I felt complacent.

419
00:16:35,370 --> 00:16:37,980
My family was happy, my bank was happy,

420
00:16:37,980 --> 00:16:39,330
but my mind wasn't.

421
00:16:39,330 --> 00:16:40,470
I wanted more.

422
00:16:40,470 --> 00:16:43,230
So, I expanded my comfort zone again

423
00:16:43,230 --> 00:16:47,250
and started posting videos
on YouTube at the age of 53.

424
00:16:47,250 --> 00:16:49,920
I'd seen so many people
on YouTube faking it,

425
00:16:49,920 --> 00:16:52,260
so I wanted to share my
knowledge and help others

426
00:16:52,260 --> 00:16:55,710
who, like me, didn't
fit the traditional path

427
00:16:55,710 --> 00:16:57,480
or those who wanted to grow their wealth

428
00:16:57,480 --> 00:16:59,010
and feel more secure in life.

429
00:16:59,010 --> 00:17:01,140
Remember, you can expand your comfort zone

430
00:17:01,140 --> 00:17:02,280
as much as you want.

431
00:17:02,280 --> 00:17:03,690
This space is infinite.

432
00:17:03,690 --> 00:17:06,090
But you have to claim it for yourself.

433
00:17:06,090 --> 00:17:08,700
If you don't push beyond
your current boundaries,

434
00:17:08,700 --> 00:17:10,860
you'll miss out on all the possibilities

435
00:17:10,860 --> 00:17:12,000
that could have been yours.

436
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:14,640
If you wanna learn what to
do every time you get paid,

437
00:17:14,640 --> 00:17:16,290
then I'll leave that video right up there,

438
00:17:16,290 --> 00:17:17,940
but don't click on it just yet.

439
00:17:17,940 --> 00:17:19,140
Make sure to subscribe

440
00:17:19,140 --> 00:17:21,060
if you want to grow your wealth, okay?

441
00:17:21,060 --> 00:17:22,260
I'll see you over there.

